column168: Veolia employees at Veolia's 10-Day facility in Schenectady, NY identified a 551A2 leaking  hazardous material on one of the trailers at the facility. The material was leaking from a small  pinhole in the side of the drum. Further investigation showed that the drum was degraded and  rusty at the bottom near where the pin hole leak occurred. It is estimated that less than 1L of  material leaked from the drum. Veolia employees over-packed the leaking container and cleaned  up the spill.
column169: Veolia Management had a discussion with the Veolia employee who accepted container for  shipment from the customer site. When doing the pick-up the Veolia employee did not see any  significant issues with the drum. Also, the Veolia employee noted while at the shipper/offer site,  the drum was partially loaded onto the truck by the shipper/offer so the employee might not  have noticed some of the degradation on the drum that caused the leaked. That Veolia employee  and EHS also discussed the importance of performing more thorough inspections of containers  before accepting for transportation in the future.   Veolia will be discussing this incident with the entire field services team during the weekly safety  training on 6/3/2020. Veolia Management will emphasize the importance and responsibility of a  thorough container inspection prior to accepting a container for transportation. Also, Veolia will  discuss solutions like over-packing containers or leaving containers on-site if they are not in good  condition to ship.

On June 1, 2020 at 0215 hours, the Wheeling and Lake Erie Rook Yard switch crew noticed a strong petroleum odor coming from TAEX 30126.  They called the yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials/Environmental Officer for the WLE.  I came out to inspect and noticed that the bottom outlet valve cap was wet and dripping.  I made sure the valve handle was fully closed and it wasn't, but even when I moved the valve handle more towards the closed position, it didn't stop the leak.  I slowly loosened the outlet cap and the initial liquid in the cap drained off and the leaked slowed.  I continued taking the cap off since i knew the ball was in the closed position.  Once I removed the cap, I looked up inside the valve and saw that product was getting past the ball valve and dripping out.  The ball looked to be in good condition.  Possibly a bad nylon seal. The pattern of product was about 3/4" wide.  I checked the gasket in the cap and it appeared to be in good shape.  I reapplied the cap and tightened it and it held.  I had the car set to another track and MarkWest called Enviroserve to transload the car.  We are currently waiting for a OTMA before moving it to a home shop for repairs.
column169: The cap should have been removed during loading to make sure it help product.

column168: During a roadside cargo inspection by the driver, he noticed an odor and upon investigation determined liquid was slowly dripping and evaporating from a weld in one leg of the IBC. The size of the crack in the weld was not visibly apparent because of the location where the leg is welded to the body of the IBC. The leak stopped after approximately 10 minutes due to no vacuum relief on the IBC and it was continually monitored by personnel at the scene including a response contractor. The facility manager transported drums and equipment to the scene and the liquid in the IBC was transferred to 55 gallon drums with no further release or incident. There was no released liquid collected due to the high rate of evaporation. The Louisiana State Police and Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality were onsite and indicated they were satisfied with the response and conclusion of the incident.
column169: The poor condition of the roadway may have contributed to the weakening of the weld during transport. The circumstances of the incident have been communicated to the drivers for heightened awareness. IBCs of this design type will continue to be examined for a similar condition prior to use.

column168: On June 5, 2020, at 0446 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal UKC contacted ERTS regarding a release of an unknown gas from cylinder tanks on trailer #311-0131. They advised that upon opening the trailer, multiple gas tanks containing toxic inhalation materials were gassing off along with strong odors that were present. ERTS dispatched Patriot Environmental to access the trailer. At 0820 EST, contractors report that they removed the DOT-4BA240 cylinders one by one off the trailer to evaluate each one for any leaks or damage – and to repalletize. They advised none of the cylinders were leaking at the time of inspection so they applied soapy water to all the valves. They noted that one cylinder UN1580, Chloropicrin) was missing the protective cap and advised there was already taped placed over it prior to shipment to prevent dust and debris from settling inside. Contractors placed a new dust cap on the cylinder that was missing one. The cylinders were monitored for leaks, but there were none and all the cylinder tanks were still full. They placed the PPE and rags used to wipe dirt and dust off the cylinders into a 55 gallon poly drum. Terminal was advised to have the trailer air out in the yard for a few days to clear the odor. It was unconfirmed how much product was in each cylinder.

Hepaco, MEI, Hull’s Environmental, Arcadis, and EnviroScience emergency response CSX contractors responded. It was determined that the tank shell had been punctured resulting in a release of approximately 8608 gallons of product.  This information was communicated to the shipper, PeroxyChem.  The leak was temporarily secured and CSX contractors transferred the remaining product.  The site was remediated and this car was cleaned and purged onsite.      NAR Cause Code: 662 – Other Describe Cause of leak (Tank shell breach due to derailment damage)  2(5+3+0) x (5+4) = 144 NARRI    Screven, GA UTLX140005, Hydrogen Peroxide

column168: Tank car TILX 193014 was found leaking methanol from between the liquid line valve and the male threaded flange it was attached to.  The liquid valve was loose (less than tool tight).

During tank car inspections with the FRA Hazmat, this car was found with a streak of product visible down the side.  Upon inspection, product was visible on the edges of the pressure plate with the combination housing cover closed. The housing was opened and liquid was found on the pressure plate and the valve.  The plug was less than tool tight, easily removed by hand, no teflon tape applied, and product sitting above the closed liquid ball valve.  The liquid was observed for approximately 5 minutes with no change in the level so the pressure was removed from the car and the liquid valve opened, allowing the product to release back into the car.  The plug was wrapped with teflon tape and properly secured.  The side of the car was wiped clean and the car released back into transportation.

column168: At approximately 09:15 PST, the TCBX 286076 was found to be leaking a small amount of diesel fuel through the manway/nozzle space when the car moved.  The car was isolated for inspection of BNSF Hazmat Responders.  Upon inspection, the manway was found to be sealed (022652) and visually in good condition.  A manway swingbolt near the hinge was found to be easily moved by hand and caused the small amount of fuel release.  The manway was fully opened to inspect the gasket, the hard lid gasket was removed and a new elastomeric nozzle gasket was placed on the car.  The lid was resecured and a new seal applied (539990).  All spilled fuel was isolated to the car body (staining only), this was cleaned with a rag and degreaser.  No impacts to the ground were noted.  The release volume is noted as only an estimate based upon responder observations.
column169: BNSF followed up with Calumet Refining to explain the finding and share the report and pictures.  Calumet should ensure that loading personnel review post load procedures on car securement.(NAR:212)

column168: On June 1, 2020, at approximately 5:45 a.m. CDT, at the above referenced R+L Carriers(RL) terminal, one(1) 90-pound bag of solid citric acid was damaged by a skid during unloading. As a result, approximately two(2) pounds released to the concrete terminal surface. RL retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from TAS Environmental(TAS) to initiate corrective actions. Following a site assessment, TAS personnel noted one(1) damaged 90-pound citric acid cylinder and approximately two(2) pounds of citric acid released to the skid and concrete surface. Using hand tools, crews collected and containerized the free product into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. TAS personnel placed the damaged cylinder into the same 55-gallon drum. 13 90-pound cylinders were repalletized for continued transportation. TAS personnel noted no further actions required onsite and demobilized.

On 6/13/20 at 1110est personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard discovered AZXX32028, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquid, N.O.S (Crude Sulfate Turpentine) Vapor Leak from the man-way. The car was isolated and the shipper (Bobby Bailey, International Paper,bobby.bailey@ipapaper.com, 409-330-768) was notified. SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a improperly installed man-way gasket (creased). The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (International Paper). Contractor personnel removed damaged gasket and installed new man-way gasket. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  NAR Cause Code: 208 – gasket misaligned  5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 70 NARRI

WAS UNLOADING THE HERMISTON TRAILER. IN THE MIDDLE OF THE LOAD A BOX WAS DISCOVERED WITH METAL SHAVINGS FALLING OUT OF IT. THE BOX WAS SENT DOWN THE BELT IN A TOTE TO THE CLERK. THEY OPENED THE PACKAGE TO PROCESS THE DAMAGE AND READ ON THE PACKING SLIP THAT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED SODIUM HYDROXIDE. THE METAL SHAVINGS ARE IRON CHIPS THAT HAD FALLEN OUT OF THEIR BOTTLE BECAUSE THE LID HAD POPPED OFF. THIS WAS CLEANED UP AND PUT BACK INTO THE BOTTLE THEN TROWN AWAY AFTER A DAMAGE REPORT HAD BEEN FILED. THE CLERK THEN CALLED ME TO COME AND HELP WITH THE BOX.

DESIGNATED RESPONDER WAS SUMMONED TO CLEAN A SPILL ON THE COUNTY SLIDE. THEY RESPONDED WITH FULL PPE   DECISION TREE, AND CLEANED THE SPILL. BROUGHT ALL AFFECTED PACKAGES BACK TO THE DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHILE SEARCHING FOR THE SDS, IT BECAME APPARENT THAT THIS WAS AN UNDECLARED. RMP CONTACTED DISTRICT COORDINATOR.

column168: UNDECLARED AEROSOLS DISCOVERED IN UPS FACILITY DURING INTERNATIONAL PACKAGE AUDIT. WHEN THEY OPENED THE PACKAGE THEY DISCOVERED A INNER BOX WITH LIMITED QUANTITY MARKING AND HAD 3 AEROSOLS INSIDE. NO MARKS OR LABELS ON OUTER CARTON. PACKAGE OFFERED USING SHIPPER NUMBER 5EY-070 THE UPS STORE 31878 DEL OBISPO STREET SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO, CA 92675. THIS SHIPMENT HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.

Driver was making a pump delivery to the customer. During the unloading, the hose ruptured resulting in a spill. The hose being used for the delivery was high pressure rated, therefore is should have not failed. However, the exact cause of the failure is unknown. The ruptured could have been from vibrations in the pumping equipment, a defective hose, or was miss handled. Once the driver was made aware of the situation, the flow of product was shut off. Next, the driver notified company personnel and the emergency cleanup company was dispatched immediately. The OEPA and NRC were then contacted right after. The contamination was removed by digging the material up and then storing it in two roll off boxes. Also, free floating product was removed via vac truck. The crew utilized fresh water to flush out the materials and to collect any free-floating product. There were also staged absorbent pads and absorbent booms used at the product collection point and left at the property to absorb any further product that may need absorbed. No product was released from the site. The clean-up was completed on June 18, 2020. All product was recovered, and the ground was treated will Micro-Blaze as a precaution. Fresh dirt and gravel were filled back in were the excavation took place. Full tanker serial number is 5HTAM4426Y7H64481, could not fit it all in the section place provided.
column169: The product was release because the equipment ruptured while the product was being unloaded. This will be prevented in the future by doing more thorough equipment inspections before delivering product. If the equipment needs to be fixed or replaced, it will then be fixed or replaced immediately before that vehicle can be used for any future deliveries. Also, all drivers will be informed of this incident at our driver led safety meetings and will be retrained as precaution on proper hose handling techniques for pump deliveries.

An Veolia employee noticed liquid in the back of a trailer. It was determined that two drums had  developed small pinhole leaks. The drums were immediately overpacked into salvage drums. All  material was absorbed and collected by the employees that found the leaks. The ground and trailer  was pressure washed. The water was collected for sampling and proper disposal. It is possible that the  waste contained sulfuric acid which could have caused the holes in the drums. The failure on both  drums was just above the bottom chime. The waste had developed pressure due to the outside  temperature and no more than 1 gal was released from the holes. No other drums from the shipment  gained pressure or showed signs of leakage however, all drums were overpacked as a preventative  measure.
column169: All future waste from this shipper will be packaged in poly drums. The generator has also changed  drum suppliers. Veolia will also speak with the shipper regarding proper classification of waste based on all chemicals present in the waste material.

column168: On 6/2/20 at approx. 2330, one of our LIN trailers developed a leak from the bottom fill valve while the trailer was in transit to customer. The driver noticed the vapor coming from the rear of the trailer as he was entering an on ramp to the Muskogee Turnpike. There was not sufficient space to safely pull over on the entrance ramp, so the driver proceeded onto the turnpike and immediately pulled over onto the shoulder of the road.  Passenger vehicles also noticed the vapor and called local authorities. The local Sheriff Dept responded to the call as the driver was evaluating the leak. The bottom fill valve was leaking and frozen in place. The driver was unable to stop the leak. The public roadway was not shutdown during the entire duration of the time spent on the shoulder. The local Sheriff Dept stayed on the scene throughout the night and was relieved by the Oklahoma Highway Patrol at 0700 the following morning. The OHP conducted a DOT inspection and put the trailer OOS due to the leaking of hazmat on the roadway.
column169: Our Fleet Maintenance Department is investigating. One corrective action is to find out if we can install sealable dust caps to prevent leaking fill valves from being able to exit trailer vessel/piping.

Contractor personnel secured the leak by transfer of product into shipper provide empty iso tank (DHDU147476), deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the release site. Once transfer completed, the loaded DHDU and the newly empty UTTU, were released to shipper with proper documentation.   This incident did not require a special switching move. column168: An Austin Powder Company driver was driving multipurpose bulk truck (MBT) Southbound on Interstate 77 in Charlotte, NC on the morning of 6/11/2020, around 10:30 AM.  His truck, a 2009 Mack GU813, (registered weight of 69,000 lbs), was fully loaded with several hazardous materials in both bulk and non-bulk quantities.  Namely, ammonium nitrate emulsion (in a DOT 412 tank), ammonium nitrate "prill", in 2 non-pressure capable bins,  a bulk quantity of diesel fuel (for manufacturing products), and a non-bulk quantity of acetic acid solution. The truck was traveling around 55 mph in heavy traffic.  The roadway is a 6-lane divided road at this point.  The truck, which was traveling in the right hand lane, swerved suddenly to the left, and then back to the right, crossing the lane and going onto the shoulder, and overturning onto the guardrail. In doing so, multiple hazardous materials were released from the vehicle.  125 gallons of combustible liquid, n.o.s. (diesel fuel) was released from the non-spec tank.  This material is on the truck for manufacturing.  The release was due to a puncture in the shell of the tank.  2 gallons of acetic acid solution was released, simply leaking from the lid as the truck lay on its side. 7,000 lbs of ammonium nitrate were released from bins (the bin door was torn off by the force of the accident), and 16,000 lbs. of ammonium nitrate emulsion was released from a DOT specification 412 tank, due to the manway lid being ripped off. In The driver reported later that he felt the rear of the vehicle "getting loose".  Examinations done at the scene found 2 u-bolts broken off on the drivers side.  These bolts hold the spring assembly to the trunion.  Evidence shows that one may have broken a short time before, and the other at the time of the accident.  The driver was transported to a local hospital and received treatment for non-life threatening injuries.  The truck was towed away, and the cleanup effort lasted several hours, keeping the road closed.  All hazardous materials were confied to the roadway.
column169: We are looking at our preventative maintenance program, and specifically developing service intervals for suspension parts, body mounts, etc (some items that may cause a sudden loss of control accident).  This truck had a PM done on May 28, 2020-at which time the suspension parts, including u bolts were checked and verified to be present, free of cracks etc.  Changes to our program may include a required replacement interval for changing out suspension parts, enhanced inspection process during PM service.  Directly after the accident, we tasked all of our locations with inspecting CMVs (particularly those with similar style suspension) for missing or damaged u-bolts.  Furthermore, we are sending a small number of u-bolts for analysis at a metallurgy lab, in hopes of finding trends related to vehicle type, use, age etc... as it relates to cracking, metal fatigue, and failure.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

The truck was towed away, and the cleanup effort lasted several hours, keeping the road closed.  All hazardous materials were confied to the roadway.
column169: We are looking at our preventative maintenance program, and specifically developing service intervals for suspension parts, body mounts, etc (some items that may cause a sudden loss of control accident).  This truck had a PM done on May 28, 2020-at which time the suspension parts, including u bolts were checked and verified to be present, free of cracks etc.  Changes to our program may include a required replacement interval for changing out suspension parts, enhanced inspection process during PM service.  Directly after the accident, we tasked all of our locations with inspecting CMVs (particularly those with similar style suspension) for missing or damaged u-bolts.  Furthermore, we are sending a small number of u-bolts for analysis at a metallurgy lab, in hopes of finding trends related to vehicle type, use, age etc... as it relates to cracking, metal fatigue, and failure.

Empire Express contacted ERTS regarding a cargo incident. It was reported that the seam on 1-55 gallon dm of UN1169, Sunshine & Lemon essential oil was compromised resulting in the release of 2-10 gallons of product. The caller stated that the drum has since been placed into a poly liner and the product is contained in the liner. Mark requested ERTS coordinate with a contractor to respond to the site to over-pack the drum and remove the standing liquid from the trailer floor and any other possible areas.  EnviroServe was dispatched to clean the release and over-pack the defective drum. Enviroserve used absorbents to collect released material and over-packed the affected drum into a 95-gallon metal over-pack drum. Once containerized, the consignee accepted the defective drum and waste.

On 06/27/20 at around 1917 hours EST CSXT personnel reported a confirmed hazmat release from tank car CTCX733789, residue Styrene Monomer Stabilized, at MP AN 000801 in New Orleans, LA.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Trinseo (Jason Scott 762-226-2337; jnscott@trinseo.com). SPSI a emergency response CSX contractors responded. It was determined that the release was coming from the liquid line valve from an unsecured plug and unsecured valve.  Additionally the vapor line plug was less than tool tight.  This information was communicated to the shipper, Trinseo.  The leak was secured and the car was placed on hold pending further inspection and pressure test of defective valve.    NAR Cause Code: 119 – Liquid line plug not secured   5(4+1+0) x (2+0) = 50 NARRI   New Orleans, LA, Styrene Monomer Stabilized

column168: Driver discovered material leaking from his trailer and pulled off the road to check on it.  He determined it was Muriatic Acid (the only chemicals on the truck) and contacted his office.  While preparing to contact emergency response a State Police vehicle pulled in to assist.  They contacted LA Hazardous Materials and helped to get the truck off the road and had him park at that weigh station at I10-W at LaPlace in St. Charles Parish.  Ideal sent another tractor and trailer with a lift gate to assist if necessary.  This truck also had a pallet of soda ash if needed for neutralization.  A representative from Ideal also came to the scene.   Ideal called US Environemental Services (USES) to stop the leak and clean up the spill.  The state sent in a sand truck to use for containment if needed.  Brian Lash,Environmental Scientist III with LDEQ also came to the scene.   USES climbed into the trailer to mitigate the spill while waiting on the fork truck order by LA Haz Mat.  The tote had leaked below the break in the container and the leak had stopped.  They removed the rest of the material from the tote at first by pumping and then by gravity.  When the forklift arrived the empty containers on the rear of the trailer were removed and decontaminated.  The full containers were then removed and decontaminated and placed on the second trailer.  The cause of the spill was determined to be that the aluminum frame broke and punctured the poly bottle of the tote.    USES then began to neutralize the spill with soda ash.  Soda ash was sprinkled on the spill and then swept up and contained.  The Haz Mat team and LDEQ determined that no other action was needed and everyone left the scene.

column168: UPON RECEIVING A CALL TO THE PSC FOR A LEAKING HAZMAT IN A TRAILER IN THE UNLOAD, I FOLLOWED MY DECISION TREE AND DISCOVERED A HAZMAT PACKAGE LEAKING IN THE MIDDLE OF THE FLOOR WITH THE ORIENTATION ARROWS POINTING HORIZONTAL. WHILE CLEANING UP THE SPILL I WAS INFORMED THAT THERE WAS AN EMPLOYEE THAT WAS EXPOSED AND HAD ALREADY WASHED OFF THE LIQUID. I THEN WENT AND LOOKED UP THE SDS. AFTER READING THE EXPOSURE SAFETY PRECAUTIONS, WENT BACK TO THE EMPLOYEE AND INSTRUCTED HIM TO GO AND WASH HIS SKIN FOR AT LEAST 15MINUTES.

THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED PALED AND SORTED TO THE SOUTH SORT AISLE. WHEN THE PACKAGE REACHED THE SOUTH SORT SORTERS IMMIDIATELY LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED THEIR SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER, FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRATE RESPONCE SHEET, PLACE THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TUB. THE EQUIPMENT WAS DECONTAMINATED FOLLOWING THE EQUIPMENT DECONTAMINATION CHECKLIST. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

I WAS CALLED TO PICK UP A LEAKER AT BAY 7 ON THE AISLE. I DONNED MY P.P.E INCLUDING APRON, BOOTS, GOOGLES,GLOVES AND WENT TO THE SPOT OF THE LEAK. THE BOX WAS WET BUT NO LIQUID HAD POOLED UP. THERE WERE A FEW DROPS OF LIQUID ON THE BELT WHICH I CLEANED AFTER I REALIZED (BY THE MARKINGS ON THE BOX) THAT THE LIQUID WAS HAND SANITIZER. I THAN BROUGHT THE BOX TO DMP FROM PROCESSING.

column168: Driver started offloading the tank trailer.  He walked to his truck to get a cup of water and didn't notice it start to leak right away where the internal valve piping is bolted up to the barrel.  Approximately 5 gallons spilled on the concrete and cleaned up by the customer.
column169: First, the drivers are never to walk away from the controls while product is actively flowing.  He was brought in for performance training.  It wouldn't have stopped the spill from happening but it certainly minimizes the amount.  The internal valve gasket was bad and was replaced along with hardware.  I believe this was a one off scenario not requiring a change in maintenance scheduling.

column168: I WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAK.CONSULTED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR CORRECT ACTIONS I DID A PH TEST. NEUTRALIZED IT TO 6PH. THEN SOLIDIFED AND BAGGED CONTENTS.

I WAS IN THE PRIMARY WITH ALL MY PPE AND SPILL CART, WENT TO BAY AND OBSERVED 2 PROPERLY LABELLED HAZ MATS THAT WERE SIDEWAYS IN THE TRUCK. THE CORNER ON ONE WAS DAMP. THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX. I UTILIZED THE DECISION TREE WHICH TOOK ME TO THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET. I SECURED THE NON DAMAGED HAZ MAT AND THEN PLACED THE DAMP PARCEL IN A LINED SPILL TUB. I OPENED THE PACKAGE TO CHECK FOR THE CAUSE OF THE DAMPNESS AND COULD NOT IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE LEAKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO PSC FOR PROCESSING THROUGH THE DMP. FOLLOWED RESPONSE SHEET; INTIAL PH READING WAS 13. SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS ADDED UNTIL THE PH WAS NEUTRAL(7). KLEXALL WAS THEN ADDED AND THE GREEN BAG PREPARED AS PER DMP PROCEDURE.

column168: On June 22,2020, at approximately 09:05 a.m. CDT, a forklift operated by R+L Carriers(R+L) personnel was operating at the above referenced terminal when the fork lift fork make contact with a 5-gallon bucket causing a puncture. As a result of the puncture, the bucket released less than one(1) gallon of acid wheel cleaner to the concrete loading dock. R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration(ER) to initiate corrective actions. The crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and deployed granular absorbents to the impacted concrete to contain the release. ER deconstructed the pallet and removed the damaged 5-gallon container. The crew placed the spent absorbents and damaged container into two(2) 55-gallon drums and staged them onsite for transport at a later date. ER scheduled their return to collect the waste and demobilized.

column168: On June 25,2020, at approximately 3:00 pm CDT, a representative with R+L Carriers(RLC) was at the above-referenced location when a 55-gallon drum of UN1263(Paint) was observed at dock door 20. As a result of the damage, approximately 30 gallons of paint was released to the dock floor. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CEIS) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Hazmat Special Services(HSS) to initiate corrective actions. Following a site assessment, crews observed a 55-gallon drum of paint with a puncture hole from a forklift and approximately 30 gallons of paint on the dock floor. HSS personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in with hand tools. The damaged 55-gallon drum was collected and containerized in one(1) 95-gallon over pack drum and all other paint impacted materials were collected and containerized in one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. HSS personnel noted no further actions required on-site and crew demobilized.

column168: A package was transported to an off-site property management facility as excess property to be assessed for continued use by the University from University of Houston Sugar Land. The package, part of a larger shipment of furniture and laboratory equipment, contained items from an experiment conducted by a group of students for the conversion of restaurant yellow grease into biodiesel. The students, at the conclusion of their work, had packed the box for storage in a laboratory space. At a later date, the laboratory area was cleaned out of excess property by administrative personnel and no inventory of the box had previously been prepared. The package was listed as "box[es] full of scrap materials" on the inventory provided. A University of Houston personnel transported the package from the Sugar Land location to the off-site property management facility where the boxes were unpacked. Property management personnel refused the box containing the hazardous materials and instructed the carrier to bring it to a third location, University of Houston Main Campus. They were specifically directed to the office of the Environmental Health & Safety Department where the hazardous materials were recognized as undeclared hazardous materials and were securely stored pending investigation.
column169: University of Houston plans to implement changes to its forms used by personnel transporting material in order to better identify when materials regulated for transportation under 49 CFR or other regulations are present. Annual training at the awareness level that covers responsibilities for positively identifying the presence of regulated materials for administrative personnel and supervisors combined with identification of positions at the University most likely to perform duties related to that of offeror will determine training requirements. Additional administrative changes to property management facility/consignee roles in rejecting shipments with unexpected hazardous materials will be investigated. Furthermore annual training will be required for positions identified as having responsibilities related to consignee.

column168: Driver was in transit with tanker load and stopped at truck stop to take a break. At approximately 10:50 pm the driver was notified that the tanker was dripping/ leaking. The local authorities were notified of the incident. The local Fire Department and Hazmat Response Team responded to the scene. They immediately put a container under the leak to catch the product and contain the leak. An Emergency Response crew was also mobilized to the scene. In addition, another tanker was mobilized to the scene in order to transfer the product from the leaking tanker. The Emergency Response crew along with the Hazmat Response Team successfully completed the transfer of the product from the leaking tanker at approximately 4:00 am. Load was delivered to intended destination. Emergency response crew remained onsite to complete the cleanup. Cleanup and disposal have been completed. Cause of the leak was determined to be gasket failure due to using the wrong gasket material that is not compatible with Nitric Acid.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Chromic acid spill at Crown Services. 24.8 gallons was lost when truck driver was attempting to unstrap the 275 gallon poly tote from the trailer etrax system. He unlatched the ratchet, then with his pallet jack lifted the tote to enable him to remove the straps hook from the etrax when the hook apparently punctured the corner of the tote approximately 1/2 of the way down from the top. The puncture was-2-3"'s in length. The tote was tilted by the pallet jack to shift the level of the product in the tote away from and below the height of the puncture to stop the leak. The majority of the spill remained on the trailer and in the parking lot at Crown while some did drain into the nearby storm drain. The New Breman Fire Dept. and the Auglaize County Emergency Management Chief was on seen to assist. We contracted Clean Harbors at 5:15 pm for HazMat clean up which continued throughout the night and next day.
column169: Corrective action internally is to review the incident with all drivers and loaders and re-tain drivers and loaders on cargo securement and proper use of straps and the etrax system.

column168: Approximately 45,607 lbs of 50% caustic membrane soda (sodium hydroxide) was released through a 2 inch manifold line valve that was left open from previous cleaning . Operator was transloading from railcar to the storage tank causing material to flow put of open line EO Plant Operator walking by noticed the spill immediately contacted the Packaging Unit in the Acid Plant. Operator closed line valve to stop the spill NRC was notified (NRC# 127910) of the spill , KDHE was notified (KDHE #47150) of the spill .  pH of the ground surface liquid was 11.5 to 13. After cleanup and removal , PH was 7

column14: I-65 S/B at US 43 on ramp
column168: Our truck driver was traveling S/B on I-65 and was in the center lane of the interstate highway. A vehicle was entering the expressway via the US Hwy 43 on ramp when that vehicle lost control and started to spin. Our driver slowed and moved into the left lane but was unable to avoid the other vehicle.  The other vehicle struck the right side of the semi -tractor near the fuel saddle tank and then spun and slid along the right side of the semi-trailer causing damage to the trailers storage box and breaking off the loading head from the belly(wet) line of compartment #5 which caused a spill of approx. 10 gallons of diesel fuel that had been the belly line,
column169: N/A Traffic accident , our driver was not at fault.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column14: I-95 SB EXIT 42 OF PA TURNPIKE
column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: The CTMV driver was traveling westbound and had just crossed over the PA-NJ Turnpike bridge and was taking the Exit 42 ramp when the sharp curve caused the tractor and tanker unit to overturn onto it passenger side striking the guardrail and coming to rest on the exit ramp. No Hazmat was released from the initial impact of the accident. However, in the process of recovering the HAZMAT contents of the compartment from the overturned CTMV some material released while changing connections during the offloading process. The material released from the packaging was contained and captured and did not enter the environment.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: On June 20th 2020, a semi truck tanker operated by Energy Dispatch , was delivering diesel fuel into an under ground storage tank at Race Trac location #2515 121 North Saginaw Boulevard. The delivery driver filled 1 tank at the location . The tank had more than enough uliage to hold the delivered gallons according to the automatic tank gauges that were utilized for this transfer. For unknown reasons, an API Junge valve began allowing Bio diesel product to pump from another tank being filled , and subsequently, said tank was overfilled. Approximately 60 gallons of fuel leaked out onto the concrete apron. The delivery driver immediately attempted to contain the spill to the immediate area with absorbent pads, snake and granular absorbent material . Approximately 5 gallons of fuel did manage to leak past the drivers efforts to contain, and entered a nearby storm drain catch basin . Energy Dispatch immediately dispatched a remediation team to handle the clean up the fuel release.
column169: It was found that the delivery driver followed all procedures and protocol during this transfer of product. An unforeseen programming failure of a Junge valve allowed too much product to pump over from another storage tank to the delivery tank. The operator believed the tank in question had more uilage than their actually was. It is recommended that Race Trac store maintenance advise any carrier delivering to this UGST to be aware of the actual uilage of the tank with space for the product being pumped in from another tank. The carrier will ensure drivers are trained how to quickly respond to spills using provided spill remediation kits.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: BOBTAIL ROLLOVER VEHICLE ACCIDENT. BOBTAIL ROLLED INTO A DITCH ON ITS SIDE , NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED. THE EMPLOYEE WAS EXTRACTED FROM THE BOBTAIL AND TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL BY AMBULANCE.  THE ROAD HAD ACURVE TO THE LEFT WHERE THE PASSENGER SIDE TIRES LEFT THE RO ADWAY HITTING THE GRAVEL ON THE ROAD CAUSING THE BOBTAIL TO ROLL ON ITS SIDE.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled,"SLIP OFF'STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders. The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the. path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn. After each such accident acommittee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: CARBAMATE PESTICIDES, LIQUID, TOXIC, FLAMMABLE, FLASH POINT NOT LESS THAN 23 DEGREES C
column168: Upon walk around inspection at truck stop, HazMat driver discovered material on the pavement and in the crash box of trailer, estimating 2 gals. was released. The material came out of a 3" cam on top of the dip tube due to one of the cam lock ears becoming loose and releasing. The driver donned his PPE and went atop trailer to tighten and secure the ear. Emergency Response Company, US Ecology, was contacted by HazMat to remediate the spill. All contaminated material was collected and deposited in a 55-gal. drum and taken off site for proper disposal.
column169: -Plant loaders to ensure all openings are sealed upon departure. -After drivers perform slosh test, when going back to spill dam, ensure that the caps/valves are all sealed. -Shipper to remove dry-break fittings and put caps so they can be sealed. -Shipper to ensure there is as a valve behind the dry-break fitting. -HazMat to work with customer to change out cam lock fittings in crashbox of all trailers servicing the work.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: Driver placed a load bar across 3 pallets of spent lead acid batteries (SLABS) in Gibsonville, NC after fueling and cargo securement check, causing contact with the terminals on a golf cart battery on the 2nd pallet from front, which was picked up in Wake Forest, NC. The cargo bar showed effects of arcing at the point of contact from the positive and negative terminals from the golf cart battery. Paper slip sheet and wafer board burned and smoldered across 3 pallets in the front, right side nose area of trailer, melting the plastic on the batteries on the top layers of the pallet. Fire smoldered out and was discovered when unloading pallet truck at domicile distribution center. Slight spill of about 1 quart of acid from batteries (SLABS) were affected by heat (melting) with no other damage. There was no damage to trailer or associated cargo. The melted batteries were individually put into 6 ml poly bags and repalletized for transport to East Penn Manufacturing Co.'s secondary lead smelter for recycle for proper disposal.
column169: The driver was retrained on load bar placement in E-Track securement. He was also retrained on top cover inspection on spent lead acid battery packaging and wrapping to ensure top cover on pallet protects all terminals against protrusion that could cause a short circuit. A tailgate  was also done with the other drivers.
